Quote: The group of colonies comprised in the New Zealand islands are composed at present of what might be termed nine principal European settlements besides smaller dependencies of these.
Notes: 1851 Aug 30 Governor Grey to Earl Grey in 1949 Rutherford ed. Select Documents 44.11 [contrast settlement] 11

Date: 30/8/1851
Source: Letter
Author: GOVERNOR GREY
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: 25. In the two islands there exist six principal towns, five of which are situated on good harbours, and each of these form emporiums for considerable colonies in their neighbourhood. 26. These five colonies were settled at different times, each upon a totally distinct plan of colonization, and by persons who proceeded direct to their respective colony, either from Great Britain or from the neighbouring Australian colonies, and who rarely passed through any other New Zealand settlement previously to reaching the colony which they now inhabit; and who ... rarely travel from their own colony to any neighbouring settlement.
Notes: 1851 Aug 30 Governor Grey to Earl Grey in 1949 Rutherford ed. Select Documents 44.25-26

